<br>
Zoning time improvements: defragment the volume holding EQ, turn on texture caching, and have at least 1GB of of DRAM installed.<br>
<br>
Frame rate improvements: reduce the number and size of the pixels on your screen; 1600x1200x32 is the most you can have.  It looks pretty, but it's also the slowest mode.  Drop down into the old 640x480x16 tiled mode for those fights when you typically LD -- F10 will take you there and back again.  Play with the texture compression.  Compressed textures load faster, but take a bit more time for some cards to process.  Uncompressed load slower, but don't require any extra processing time.  Depending on the card and your system's bus bandwidth, one will be faster than the other (and it might be either one).<br>
<br>
Windows VM: don't check &quot;let windows manage swap for me&quot;.  Windows is incredibly poor at doing this.  Ideally, you'll want to setup your disk with 3 partitions: C|D|E.  Put Windows and other system stuff on C, put games and other large things on E, and make ALL of D your swap.  Force D to be a FAT file system with 32K clusters.  It should be roughly 2-4 times the size of the DRAM installed in your system.  If you don't want to repartition, just make a fixed size swap file 2-4 times the size of DRAM.  This will help a great deal on systems with low DRAM (under 512MB), less for systems with more DRAM.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> First, EQ uses UDP for data transport. Lost packets are lost packets, and are never resent.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This shows a misconception.  UDP just means the transport layer doesn't automatically resend and order the packets before they reach the EQ client.  EQ uses UDP, but has it's own protocol on top of that.  Some things are just dropped and never resent.  Notice how things &quot;ghost and warp&quot;?  Mob positions are one of those things that are never resent.  Every ghost you see is a dropped position packet.  Notice how you always send/receive chat even in the worst PL situations?  It might lag horribly, but you get it.  Chat is resent until server/client acknowledges receipt.<br>
<br>
Bandwidth improvements: you can help your bandwidth (network performace) with /serverfilter on.  There's no real reason you ever want it off.  Also, turn off as much chat as you can.  The more you turn off, the less you'll receive.  Remember that chat is never dropped?  If your system is dropping chat packets, the server will just send more and more (new ones and resent old ones).  Your performance will get worse and worse in a viscious downward spiral to LD.  Turn off damage shields, criticals, bard songs, auction, ooc, say, and most especially spell chat.  /Leave as many channels as you can -- particularly the high spam channels like market and auction. <p>Mosushi, Lizard Master of the Fish<br>
